    "created_at": "2013-05-02T17:33:42Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-05-02T17:33:42Z",
    "body": "From what I can tell, the C++ nullptr_t has more to do with overloading based on arguments---that is, one problem with using `0` as a NULL was that it could be interpreted as either an integer or a pointer. Reinterpret casting `nullptr` to an integer has the same semantics as reinterpret casting `(void*)0`, which I guess is...semi-defined?\n",
